						               													<description>Step back into a dark period in human history when frenzy and paranoia dominated peoples&amp;rsquo; perception of &amp;lsquo;the other&amp;rsquo;, driving communities throughout Europe to take the most extreme measures against their fellow man&amp;hellip; or woman, as history would have it.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;Burn the Witch&amp;quot; is a game of social deduction designed for five to fifteen players divided into two factions pitted against one another in their bid for survival. Players represent houses, comprised of two to four villagers, acting on behalf of either the zealots or the witches they are pursuing. With witches forming a minority, their only chance for survival is dependent on players' ability to employ cunning and misdirection as they seek to outwit the others at the table, turning their neighbors&amp;rsquo; paranoia and pyromania back onto themselves.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game typically runs 45-75 minutes and concludes when either every last witch has been enkindled or enough zealots have been condemned to the stake they no longer hold a majority, at which point the hunt draws to a close, and the witches win.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
